      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a portfolio folder?</summary>
        <p>A portfolio folder is a physical or digital organizational system where an investor stores critical documents related to their investments, such as brokerage statements, trade confirmations, research notes, and tax forms.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why do I need a portfolio folder if everything is online?</summary>
        <p>Even with online brokerages, having your own dedicated portfolio folder helps you track your investment thesis, maintain records for tax purposes in case of audits or broker changes, and provides a clear, distraction-free view of your financial strategy.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What should be included in a portfolio folder?</summary>
        <p>Your folder should include a summary of your investment goals, monthly or quarterly account statements, trade confirmations, records of dividends received, research reports on individual assets, and essential tax documents like 1099s.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How often should I update my portfolio folder?</summary>
        <p>It is recommended to update your portfolio folder at least quarterly to coincide with earnings seasons and statement generations, or whenever you make a significant trade or receive important tax documents.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is a digital portfolio folder better than a physical one?</summary>
        <p>A digital folder offers easier searchability and backup capabilities (like cloud storage), while a physical folder can be more secure against cyber threats and provides a tangible way to review documents. Many successful investors use a hybrid approach.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
